user_message:
An agent A claimed that the following process_short_params_str code violates the MISRA C 2023 rule 17.8.
<misra_rule>
MISRA C 2023 Rule 17.8 is A function parameter should not be modified.
Note that the object referred to by a pointer parameter may be modified, but the pointer itself shall not be modified.
</misra_rule>
<target_code>
Here is the original code of process_short_params_str.
```c
static enum PerfRepl_param_result
process_short_params_str (const char *params_str, const char *next_param)
{
  if (0 == params_str[0])
  {
    fprintf (stderr, "Unrecognised parameter: -\n");
    return PERF_RPL_PARAM_ERROR;
  }
  do
  {
    enum PerfRepl_param_result param_res;
    param_res = process_short_param (params_str, next_param);
    if (PERF_RPL_PARAM_ONE_CHAR != param_res)
      return param_res;
  } while (0 != (++params_str)[0]);
  return PERF_RPL_PARAM_FULL_STR;
}
```
</target_code>
<response format>
Provide your answer with these fields.
- explanation: your evaluation of the scenario provided by the agent A.
- is_report_correct: whether the report is correct or not (true/false). True means there is a violation.
</response format>
<scenario>
The agent A provided the following violation scenario:
The loop condition uses (++params_str)[0], which increments the function parameter 'params_str' and thus modifies the pointer parameter itself. This violates MISRA C 2023 Rule 17.8 (pointer parameters may be used to modify the pointee but the pointer value must not be changed).
</scenario>

